Lombok&#39;s [@Builder annotation](https://projectlombok.org/features/Builder) can be applied to a constructor, not just the class itself. So you can create a constructor that generates the ID, and apply the annotation to that like so:

```
public class Car {

@Builder
public Car(UUID id, String brand, String model) {
    this.id = id == null ? UUID.randomUUID() : id;
    this.brand = brand;
    this.model = model;
}
```

I have encountered the same problem and I was surprised I didn&#39;t find a documented solution for Hibernate 6, but I have finally came up with the solution that works. Hibernate comes with `org.hibernate.id.uuid.UuidGenerator`, but just extending it does not make it work. The `org.hibernate.cfg.AnnotationBinder.createGenerator()` will create your generator only if it&#39;s configured properly. What createGenerator does is it tries to get a constructor of your Generator class, but it must have the proper Annotation type. So you have to define your own annotation type for id generation and pass it as a parameter to the constructor of your generator. The problem here is that the annotations cannot be extended in Java, so I needed a little tweak to make the `super()` constructor of the `UuidGenerator` work. Here is my solution:

First, define your annotation class:

```java
@IdGeneratorType( CarIdGenerator.class )
@Retention(RetentionPolicy.RUNTIME)
@Target({ FIELD, METHOD })
public @interface CarUuidGenerator {
    /**
     * Which style of generation should be used
     */
    UuidGenerator.Style style() default UuidGenerator.Style.TIME;

}
```

Now your `CarIdGenerator` class:

```java
public class CarIdGenerator extends UuidGenerator {

    public CarIdGenerator(
// You need your annotation instance here so that the AnnotationBinder can pick the right constructor
        CarUuidGenerator config,
        Member idMember,
        CustomIdGeneratorCreationContext creationContext
    ) {
// the superclass constructor won&#39;t take CarUuidGenerator as a parameter, and annotations cannot be extended, so we need to instantiate  UuidGenerator annotation manually:      
super(getUuidGeneratorAnnotation(config.style()), idMember, creationContext);
    }

    @Override
    public Serializable generate(SharedSessionContractImplementor session, Object obj) {
        if ((obj != null) &amp;&amp; (obj instanceof Car)) {
            Car carEntity = (Car) obj;
            if (carEntity.getId() == null) {
                return (Serializable) super.generate(session, obj);
            }
            return carEntity.getId();
        }
        return (Serializable) super.generate(session, obj);
    }

    private static org.hibernate.annotations.UuidGenerator getUuidGeneratorAnnotation(org.hibernate.annotations.UuidGenerator.Style style) {
        return new org.hibernate.annotations.UuidGenerator() {
            @Override
            public Class&lt;? extends Annotation&gt; annotationType() {
                return org.hibernate.annotations.UuidGenerator.class;
            }

            @Override
            public Style style() {
                return style;
            }
        };
    }
}
```

Finally, you can annotate your `Car` entity class:


```java
public class Car {

@Id
@CarUuidGenerator
private UUID id;

}

```

