_**Preface:** The other answers already solve your problem, but I thought I&#39;d add some explanation._

---

# Problems

There are a few problems with your code, all discussed below.

## Uninitialized Fields

The most immediate problem is the following error when you run the program and press the button.

```lang-none
Exception in thread &quot;JavaFX Application Thread&quot; java.lang.NullPointerException: Children: child node is null: parent = Group@2a18a4be
        at javafx.graphics/javafx.scene.Parent$3.onProposedChange(Parent.java:543)
        at javafx.base/com.sun.javafx.collections.VetoableListDecorator.addAll(VetoableListDecorator.java:233)
        at javafx.base/com.sun.javafx.collections.VetoableListDecorator.addAll(VetoableListDecorator.java:103)
        at javafx.graphics/javafx.scene.Group.&lt;init&gt;(Group.java:106)
        at four_color_wheel.processButtonPress(four_color_wheel.java:76)
        ...
```

This is thrown in this method:

```lang-java
public void processButtonPress(ActionEvent event) {
    Group circle = new Group(blueArc, greenArc, yellowArc, redArc);
    circle.setRotate(90);
}
```

Because `blueArc`, `greenArc`, `yellowArc`, and `redArc` are all null. A parent in JavaFX cannot have null children.

Your class has fields that you never initialize. Instead, you create local variables with the same name in the `start` method. Those local variables hide/shadow the fields in the context of the `start` method. But the `processButtonPress` method is referencing the fields (because the local variables of the `start` method are out of scope). To fix this, simply initialize the fields instead of creating local variables.

For example, instead of:

```lang-java
// Blue Arc
Arc blueArc = new Arc(200, 200, 150, 150, 0, 90);
blueArc.setType(ArcType.ROUND);
blueArc.setStroke(Color.BLUE);
blueArc.setFill(Color.BLUE);
```

Do:

```lang-java
// Blue Arc
blueArc = new Arc(200, 200, 150, 150, 0, 90);
blueArc.setType(ArcType.ROUND);
blueArc.setStroke(Color.BLUE);
blueArc.setFill(Color.BLUE);
```

By not having the type in front of the `blueArc = ...` you are assigning the field instead of creating a local variable. Do the same for all your fields.

## Rotating the Wrong Group

This method:

```lang-java
public void processButtonPress(ActionEvent event) {
    Group circle = new Group(blueArc, greenArc, yellowArc, redArc);
    circle.setRotate(90);
}
```

Is creating a new `Group`. This causes two issues:

1. You are rotating a `Group` that is not being displayed in the UI. Thus, the rotation has no visible effect.

2. A node in JavaFX cannot belong to two parents. By creating a new `Group` and adding the arcs to it, those arcs are implicitly removed from their current `Group` first. This will remove the arcs from the displayed UI.

The fix is to reference the field `circle` instead of creating a new `Group`.

```lang-java
public void processButtonPress(ActionEvent event) {
    circle.setRotate(90);
}
```

The above assumes you&#39;ve initialized the `circle` field as discussed in the previous section.

## You Set the Rotation to a Constant

I assume you want the &quot;circle&quot; to rotate **by** 90 degrees every time you press the button. To do this, you need to _add_ 90 degrees to the _current_ rotation.

```lang-java
circle.setRotation(circle.getRotation() + 90);
```

Otherwise, with your current code, the circle will rotate **to** 90 degrees upon the first button press, and then will never rotate again.

## No Animation

This is not a problem _per se_. However, it is typically good to use animations for this sort of thing. It lets the user see the results of their actions clearly and can also help direct the user&#39;s attention. You can use a `Timeline` to implement the animation, but in this case it would probably be cleaner to use a `RotateTransition`. See the example at the end of this answer for more information.

## Not Following Standard Naming Conventions

You should always follow the naming and formatting conventions of your team or organization (or, if you&#39;re working alone, the conventions you choose--just be consistent). But when posting code on a public forum like Stack Overflow, you should follow the _standard_ naming and formatting conventions of the programming language. In Java, class names should follow `PascalCase`, also known as `UpperCamelCase`.

In other words, your class should be named:

```lang-java
public class FourColorWheel extends Application {
   ...
}
```

---

# Example

Here&#39;s your code with fixes for the problems discussed above. There were also some other modifications made to make the code cleaner, including:

* Generalizing the creation of a multi-colored &quot;circle&quot;, allowing a circle with any number of colors to be made.

* Only keeping fields that were absolutely needed (because those objects needed to be referenced between methods). It&#39;s typically a good idea to keep things as narrowly scoped as possible when programming.

* Using an `HBox` instead of a `FlowPane` to give a better initial layout. This change was only for the example; using a `FlowPane` is not wrong (assuming it&#39;s the right layout for your real program).

* Disabling the button while the animation is running so it can&#39;t accidentally be restarted in the middle of a rotation.

Here&#39;s the code:

```lang-java
import javafx.animation.RotateTransition;
import javafx.application.Application;
import javafx.event.ActionEvent;
import javafx.geometry.Insets;
import javafx.geometry.Pos;
import javafx.scene.Group;
import javafx.scene.Scene;
import javafx.scene.control.Button;
import javafx.scene.layout.HBox;
import javafx.scene.paint.Color;
import javafx.scene.shape.Arc;
import javafx.scene.shape.ArcType;
import javafx.stage.Stage;
import javafx.util.Duration;

import static javafx.animation.Animation.Status.RUNNING;

public class FourColorWheel extends Application {

    private RotateTransition animation;

    @Override
    public void start(Stage primaryStage) {
        Group circle = createMultiColorCircle(Color.BLUE, Color.GREEN, Color.YELLOW, Color.RED);

        animation = new RotateTransition(Duration.millis(175), circle);
        animation.setByAngle(90);

        Button rotate = new Button(&quot;Rotate Right&quot;);
        rotate.disableProperty().bind(animation.statusProperty().isEqualTo(RUNNING));
        rotate.setOnAction(this::handleButtonPress);
    
        HBox pane = new HBox(20, circle, rotate);
        pane.setAlignment(Pos.CENTER);
        pane.setPadding(new Insets(20));
    
        Scene scene = new Scene(pane);
        primaryStage.setTitle(&quot;Four-Color Wheel&quot;);
        primaryStage.setScene(scene);
        primaryStage.show();
    }

    private void handleButtonPress(ActionEvent event) {
        event.consume();
        animation.playFromStart();
    }

    private Group createMultiColorCircle(Color... colors) {
        Group circle = new Group();

        double startAngle = 0.0;
        double length = 360.0 / colors.length;
        for (Color color : colors) {
            Arc arc = new Arc(200, 200, 150, 150, startAngle, length);
            arc.setType(ArcType.ROUND);
            arc.setStroke(color);
            arc.setFill(color);
            circle.getChildren().add(arc);

            startAngle += length;
        }

        return circle;
    }
}
```

