answers.body_markdown:
the reason is here：
        
    Integer a = -1;
    Integer b = Integer.MIN_VALUE;

    System.out.println(b); // -2147483648
    System.out.println(-b); // -2147483648

    System.out.println(a); // -1
    System.out.println(-a); // 1

If you want to use the result of compareTo to judge, for example:

    Integer a = x.compareTo(y)
    
    
    if(-a &gt; 0) {
        
        //do something
    
    }

If the return value of `compareTo` is `Integer.MIN_VALUE`, then the value of `-a` is equal to the value of `a` both are `-2147483648`, so the result is wrong

Let&#39;s say you do return `MIN_VALUE`:

```
class PossiblyBadlyWrittenClass implements Comparable&lt;PossiblyBadlyWrittenClass&gt; {
    @NotNull private final int value;

    @Override
    public int compareTo(@NotNull PossiblyBadlyWrittenClass o) {
        if (value &gt; o.value) {
            return Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        } else if (value &lt; o.value) {
            return Integer.MIN_VALUE;
        } else {
            return 0;
        }
    }

    // constructor, and other boilerplate...
}
```

Now someone else comes along and uses this `PossiblyBadlyWrittenClass` in their class. They want their class&#39; natural order to be the *reverse* order of how `PossiblyBadlyWrittenClass` is ordered.

One way someone would do this, is to negate whatever your implementation of `compareTo` returns. They&#39;d think that by using `+`, if your `compareTo` returns a positive numbers, then theirs would return a negative number, and vice versa.

```
class SomethingElse implements Comparable&lt;SomethingElse&gt; {
    @NotNull private final PossiblyBadlyWrittenClass foo;

    @Override
    public int compareTo(@NotNull SomethingElse o) {
        return -foo.compareTo(o.foo);
    }

    // ...
}
```

But this is not the case! When your `compareTo` returns `Integer.MIN_VALUE` (a negative number), applying the unary `-` operator to it gives you `Integer.MIN_VALUE` again, because of overflow.

`MIN_VALUE` is `-2147483648`. Mathematically, if you negate that, you get `2147483648`. But `Integer.MAX_VALUE` is `2147483647`, just 1 smaller. Therefore, the mathematically correct result cannot be represented as an `int`. The value &quot;wraps around&quot; to the negatives.

So now their `compareTo` has a bug.

Of course, you might argue that this is that person&#39;s fault as they did not consider this edge case. And that they should have written it like this instead:

```
return o.foo.compareTo(foo);
```

But then people using *that* code will need to be careful too. It would be much easier if you never returned `MIN_VALUE` in the first place, so nobody would need to worry about this edge case.

